Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it creates an in-memory `TestServer` and gives you an `HttpClient` that talks to it over HTTP without opening a real port.

### Setup

```csharp
// Add these NuGet packages to your test project:
// Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
// xunit (or your preferred test framework)

public class McpTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsServerCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2.0", body.GetProperty("jsonrpc").GetString());
        Assert.Equal(1, body.GetProperty("id").GetInt32());
        var result = body.GetProperty("result");
        Assert.True(result.TryGetProperty("capabilities", out _));
    }
}
```

### Key points

1. **`WebApplicationFactory<Program>`** boots your real `Program` / `Startup` pipeline in-process — middleware, DI, routing all run.
2. **`CreateClient()`** returns an `HttpClient` wired to the in-memory server. No TCP port needed.
3. **Override services** for test doubles:

```csharp
var factory = new WebApplicationFactory<Program>()
    .WithWebHostBuilder(builder =>
    {
        builder.ConfigureServices(services =>
        {
            services.AddSingleton<IMyDependency, FakeDependency>();
        });
    });
```

4. **For SSE (Streamable HTTP)**, use `SendAsync` with `HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead` and read the response stream incrementally:

```csharp
var request = new HttpRequestMessage(HttpMethod.Post, "/mcp");
request.Content = JsonContent.Create(initRequest);
request.Headers.Accept.Add(new("text/event-stream"));

var response = await _client.SendAsync(request,
    HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead);

using var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);

while (await reader.ReadLineAsync() is { } line)
{
    // Parse SSE frames: "data: {...}"
    if (line.StartsWith("data: "))
    {
        var json = JsonDocument.Parse(line[6..]);
        // assert on each event
    }
}
```

5. **Make `Program` visible** to the test project by adding to your server's `Program.cs` (or using `InternalsVisibleTo`):

```csharp
// Bottom of Program.cs
public partial class Program { }
```

This gives you true end-to-end MCP protocol coverage (serialization, routing, headers, status codes) with the speed of an in-process call.
